\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Assume the outcome is now a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 with derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $g'$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{i}=g_{i}\left(s\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i}\mid Z_{i}=1\right]-\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i}\mid Z_{i}=0\right] & =\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{s_{0i}}^{s_{1i}}g_{i}'\left(j\right)\mathrm{d}j\right]\\
 & =\int\mathbb{E}\left[g_{i}'\left(j\right)\mid s_{1i}>j>s_{0i}\right]P\left(s_{1i}>j>s_{0i}\right)\mathrm{d}j
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Where the first line is fundamental thm of calculus, the second uses independenc
e.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Continuous ACR
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i}\mid Z_{i}=1\right]-\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i}\mid Z_{i}=0\right]}{\mathbb{E}\left[s_{i}\mid Z_{i}=1\right]-\mathbb{E}\left[s_{i}\mid Z_{i}=0\right]}=\frac{\int\mathbb{E}\left[g_{i}'\left(j\right)\mid s_{1i}>j>s_{0i}\right]P\left(s_{1i}>j>s_{0i}\right)\mathrm{d}j}{\int P\left(s_{1i}>j>s_{0i}\right)\mathrm{d}j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Similar to before, but derivative turns out to play a very important point
 in education lit!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Important special case when:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{i}(s)=\alpha_{0i}+\alpha_{1i}s,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i}\mid Z_{i}=1\right]-\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i}\mid Z_{i}=0\right]}{\mathbb{E}\left[s_{i}\mid Z_{i}=1\right]-\mathbb{E}\left[s_{i}\mid Z_{i}=0\right]}=\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[\alpha_{1i}\left(S_{1i}-S_{0i}\right)\right]}{\mathbb{E}\left[S_{1i}-S_{0i}\right]}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Weighted average of random coefficients, 
\emph on
weighted by how much schooling shifts.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note on Special Case
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Thanks to continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\cdot)$
\end_inset

, we can always use the mean value theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}_{i}\in\left[S_{i0},S_{i1}\right]$
\end_inset

 such that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{i}\left(S_{1i}\right)=g_{i}\left(S_{i0}\right)+g_{i}'\left(\tilde{S}_{i}\right)\left(S_{1i}-S_{i0}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus we always have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i}\mid Z_{i}=1\right]-\mathbb{E}\left[Y_{i}\mid Z_{i}=0\right]}{\mathbb{E}\left[s_{i}\mid Z_{i}=1\right]-\mathbb{E}\left[s_{i}\mid Z_{i}=0\right]}=\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[g_{i}'\left(\tilde{S}_{i}\right)\left(S_{1i}-S_{0i}\right)\right]}{\mathbb{E}\left[S_{1i}-S_{0i}\right]}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Back to School
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Card (2001) assumes HK model with returns to schooling:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(s_{i}\right)=\log y_{i}=\alpha_{i}+b_{i}s_{i}-\frac{1}{2}k_{1}s_{i}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

optimal schooling is then (see Card, 2001 for details):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{i}^{\star}=\frac{\left(b_{i}-r_{i}\right)}{k},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the individual's discount rate.
 Two implications:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
By concavity, returns to schooling at low 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 are higher: 
\begin_inset Formula $g''(s_{i})<0$
\end_inset

!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Individuals with a high discount factor choose less education
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Implications of ACR for Returns to Schooling
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Given the above, the ACR estimated with an IV that reduces schooling costs
 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[g_{i}'\left(\tilde{S}_{i}\right)\left(S_{1i}-S_{0i}\right)\right]}{\mathbb{E}\left[S_{1i}-S_{0i}\right]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the real world, reduction in costs affects more people with 
\emph on
low schooling, 
\emph default
which means:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1i}-S_{0i}$
\end_inset

 is largest for people with lower 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0i}$
\end_inset

, get more weight in ACR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}'\left(\tilde{S}_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 is larger for people with low 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[g_{i}'\left(\tilde{S}_{i}\right)\left(S_{1i}-S_{0i}\right)\right]}{\mathbb{E}\left[S_{1i}-S_{0i}\right]}>\mathbb{E}\left[g_{i}'\left(S_{i}\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is called 
\emph on
discount rate bias
\emph default
 since in the model low 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0i}$
\end_inset

 happens because of high 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
