\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The literature on schooling 
\emph on
almost always 
\emph default
finds IV estimates that are larger than OLS 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
e.g., Angrist and Krueger (1991) have OLS 0.07, and IV 0.10
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Ability bias is positive, measurement error is negative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
AK say ability bias is small, so measurement error dominates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Discount rate bias produces larger estimates regardless!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Policy relevance:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Measurement error has no real-world implications...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
...
 but discount rate has: estimates are high just because of population of
 compliers
\end_layout

\end_deeper
